    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-10-26T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-10-26T03:00:00-05:00" n="408"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d408">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/10–2648: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-10-26T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 26, 1948—4 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 27—4:58 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>302. According KMA report from Chinwangtao, Government troops there openly saying
                    they have no intention fighting if Communists arrive, but will turn over to
                    Communists. This is further indication deterioration morale Government forces.
                    Troops concerned units of Ninety-second Army under Fu Tso-yi’s command but not
                    his own troops. So far we have heard no such reports about Fu’s own <pb
                        facs="0528" n="518" xml:id="pg_518"/> troops; Chinese officials Tientsin
                    greatly concerned over food question. Relaxation police control over prices has
                    resulted some supplies coming in from countryside, but reported Communist
                    standing offer 30 percent premium over any Government prices offered for wheat
                    and other grains expected prevent much from coming in.</p>
                <p>KMA states if food not available for 60,000 mine workers Tangshan area, many must
                    go over to Communists’ areas to eat. ECA assisting but Chinese Government
                    apparently unwilling or unable to relieve situation.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">New Star</hi>, daily paper published here by graduates
                    Yenching University, published bitter editorial yesterday entitled “We Must Have
                    Peace”. This is first editorial in Tientsin openly demanding peace. Translation
                    sent in our telegram 547, October 26.<note n="10" xml:id="d408fn10">To Nanking;
                        repeated to the Department as No. 304, not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Nanking 546, repeated Department 302, Shanghai 514, Peiping arid Mukden.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
